value.value: A WHO grade I meningioma characterized by the presence of intercellular microcystic spaces that contain mucinous fluid.
A malignant neoplasm involving the bile duct
A malignant neoplasm involving the biliary tree
A benign mesenchymal neoplasm arising from smooth, skeletal, or cardiac muscle tissue.
A benign neoplasm that involves the intestine.
A benign papillary neoplasm composed of transitional cells and characterized by an endophytic growth pattern.

A benign neoplasm that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the nasal cavity. It results from the invagination and proliferation of epithelial cells in the underlying stroma. Clinical manifestations include nasal obstruction, epistaxis, and anosmia. It has the tendency to recur and extend to adjacent structures. Inverted papillomas are occasionally associated with the development or presence of carcinomas, usually squamous cell carcinomas.
Inflammation of the submandibular lymph nodes.
Inflammation of the cervical lymph nodes.
Inflammation of the postauricular lymph nodes.
A form of lymphadenitis that is characterized by formation of pus; it is most often caused by staphylococcal or streptococcal bacteria.
An infection of the lymph nodes in the axilla.
A malignant neoplasm involving the retina.

Trilateral retinoblastoma refers to bilateral (or less often unilateral) retinoblastoma associated with an intracranial primitive neuroectodermal tumor in the pineal or suprasellar region. This syndrome is often associated with a increased familial incidence of retinoblastoma. (From Cancer 86(1): 135-141, 1999).

Retinoblastoma involving both eyes. This occurs in the majority of patients with the inherited variant. A minority of patient with bilateral retinoblastoma were found to have involvement of the pineal gland as well.
A retinoblastoma that only involves a single eye.
Retinoblastoma restricted to local involvement.
Retinoblastoma that has spread beyond the eye e.g. to brain, soft tissue/bone, bone marrow.

A localized tumor composed of sheets of mast cells without atypia. It includes the cutaneous mastocytoma which involves the dermis and subcutaneous tissue, and the extracutaneous mastocytoma. Most cases of extracutaneous mastocytoma have been reported in the lung.

A disorder of the thalamus. Causes include brain neoplasms, cerebrovascular disorders, brain trauma, brain hypoxia, infections, and brain hemorrhage. Signs and symptoms include movement and sensory abnormalities, visual abnormalities, ataxia, and coma.
A rare slow growing benign tumor of aberrant and ectatic venous connections.
Neuropathy resulting from uremia.
A corneal disease that is characterized by inflammation of the cornea.

A rare primary thymic carcinoma, characterized by the presence of squamous cells, intermediate type cells, and mucus-producing cells. Published information on clinical course is limited to single-case reports.
A carcinoma of the breast characterized by pools of mucin and islands of malignant squamous cells. Mucoepidermoid carcinomas of the breast are extremely rare.
A hemangioma arising from skeletal muscle.
A mucoepidermoid carcinoma that arises from the extrahepatic bile ducts.
A carcinoma that arises from epithelial cells of the extrahepatic bile duct.
A mucoepidermoid carcinoma that involves the zone of skin.
An extremely rare carcinoma that arises from the lacrimal gland. It is characterized by the presence of infiltrating nests of epidermoid cells and mucus producing cells.
A rare carcinoma of the esophagus which contains squamous cells, mucus secreting cells, and cells of an intermediate type. (WHO)
A rare mucoepidermoid carcinoma of the larynx. It usually arises from the supraglottic area. Hoarseness and dysphagia are the presenting symptoms.
A hemangioma arising from the deep soft tissues.

A neurogenic tumor that arises from the mediastinum. Neural tumors are the most common tumors that arise from the posterior mediastinum. Representative examples include Schwannoma, neurofibroma, and neuroblastoma.
A neoplasm (disease) that involves the nerve plexus.

Benign and malignant neoplasms arising from one or more of the cervical, thoracic, lumbar, sacral, or coccygeal nerve roots. The majority of these tumors are benign. Clinical manifestations may include pain, weakness and loss of sensation along the course of the involved nerve root. Large tumors may cause spinal cord compression.
A malignant neoplasm involving the epicardium.
A disease involving the prostate gland.
Malignant neoplasms which arise or occur within the intracranial cavity below the tentorium cerebelli. This includes neoplasms within the brain and/or surrounding spaces.
A meningioma that affects the foramen magnum.
A hemangioma arising from the skin.

A neoplasm with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the stomach. It includes well differentiated neuroendocrine tumors (low and intermediate grade) and poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinomas (high grade).
A malignant germ cell tumor that arises from the stomach. It includes choriocarcinoma and immature teratoma.
A malignant germ cell tumor that develops as a primary tumor in an anatomic site other than the testis or ovary.
A hemangioma arising from the subglottic area.
A category of psychiatric disorders which are characterized by the presence of physical symptoms that suggest a medical condition but are not fully explained by any known medical reasons.

An uncommon usually benign neoplasm that arises from the testis. It is characterized by the presence of cysts lined by transitional cells and solid nests of transitional cells in a spindle cell stroma.
